**Code Explanation:**

The code implements the first step of the research plan: Data Pre-processing and cILC Construction. 1. DataLoader Class: A robust DataLoader is defined to handle patch-based loading of the FLAMINGO Component-Separation dataset. It includes methods to load ground truth components, SO LAT noise, Planck noise (with appropriate unit conversions from MJy/sr and K_CMB to µK_CMB), and the observed stacked signals. 2. Empirical Noise Covariance: The script loads all 3000 realizations of the SO LAT noise maps for 90, 150, and 217 GHz. It computes the 2D Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) using an orthonormal normalization to preserve variance. The empirical 3x3 noise covariance matrix is then computed for each spatial frequency (k_x, k_y) by averaging the cross-power spectra over all realizations. 3. cILC Weights Construction: The constrained Internal Linear Combination (cILC) weights are computed in harmonic space. The constraint matrix A is built using the tSZ spectral response (to be preserved, W^T a_tSZ = 1) and the kSZ spectral response (to be nulled, W^T a_kSZ = 0). Since the kSZ response is frequency-independent in µK_CMB (just like the primary CMB), nulling kSZ automatically nulls the CMB. A Tikhonov regularization term proportional to the local trace of the covariance matrix is added to penalize large weights, minimizing residual variance and mitigating CIB leakage. 4. Verification and Saving: The script analytically verifies the constraints by computing the dot product of the weights with the spectral responses and printing the maximum absolute errors. Finally, the computed weights and covariance matrix are saved to the data/ directory, and a quick test is performed on the first noise realization to demonstrate the noise suppression achieved by the cILC weights.

