**Code Explanation:**

The code performs feature engineering and normalization for the Super-Resolution Denoising Autoencoder (SR-DAE). It constructs a 6-channel feature tensor for each of the 1523 sky patches. The features include three spectral difference maps (150-90 GHz, 217-150 GHz, 353-217 GHz) and three CIB auxiliary channels (353 GHz, 545 GHz, 857 GHz). To account for beam smoothing differences, the higher-resolution map in each difference pair is smoothed to match the lower-resolution map using a Gaussian beam window function in Fourier space. Specifically, the 217 GHz SO map (1.0 arcmin) is smoothed to 4.5 arcmin before being subtracted from the 353 GHz Planck map, explicitly addressing the beam differences between Planck-band and SO-band channels. The ground truth CIB maps (in Jy/sr) are converted to µK_CMB using utils.jysr2uk, smoothed from their native 1 arcmin resolution to the respective Planck beams, and combined with Planck noise realizations to simulate the auxiliary channels. Normalization is performed using local variance estimates: for each patch, the exact noise realization is isolated, its standard deviation is computed, and the corresponding feature map is divided by this local noise standard deviation. Finally, global robust scaling (subtracting the median and dividing by the interquartile range) is applied to the CIB auxiliary channels to ensure consistent dynamic ranges. The processed features and the random noise indices used are saved for reproducibility in subsequent steps.

